106
00:06:09,869 --> 00:06:11,371
(PEOPLE GASPING)

107
00:06:11,454 --> 00:06:13,331
(RUMBLING)
(GEARS RATTLING)

108
00:06:15,959 --> 00:06:17,544
(OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING)

109
00:06:22,299 --> 00:06:24,301
(PEOPLE MURMURING)

110
00:06:25,802 --> 00:06:27,345
(PEOPLE GASPING)

111
00:06:39,149 --> 00:06:41,985
(CLICKING)

112
00:06:42,068 --> 00:06:44,070
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

113
00:06:47,073 --> 00:06:48,950
(MUSIC CRESCENDOS AND STOPS)

114
00:06:49,826 --> 00:06:51,828
(MUSIC RESUMES)

115
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:39,769
(PHONE RINGING)
(GASPS)

116
00:08:39,853 --> 00:08:41,521
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

117
00:08:49,320 --> 00:08:50,739
(BEEPS)
Hello?

118
00:08:51,239 --> 00:08:52,407
MIKE: (OVER PHONE)
<i>Hey, it's me.</i>

119
00:08:52,490 --> 00:08:53,742
Mike.

120
00:08:53,825 --> 00:08:54,909
What time is it?

121
00:08:55,410 --> 00:08:57,871
MIKE: Oh, <i>uh,
it's early. Sorry.</i>

122
00:08:57,954 --> 00:08:59,622
<i>Did I... did I wake you up?</i> No.

123
00:08:59,706 --> 00:09:02,751
I mean, yes, you did,
but, uh...

124
00:09:04,085 --> 00:09:05,462
<i>I had a rough night.</i>

125
00:09:05,962 --> 00:09:07,756
Bad dreams again? Or...

126
00:09:07,839 --> 00:09:09,382
VANESSA: <i>I can't seem
to catch a break.</i>

127
00:09:09,466 --> 00:09:10,508
Mmm.

128
00:09:11,009 --> 00:09:12,051
Anything that I can do
to help?

129
00:09:12,135 --> 00:09:13,344
VANESSA: <i>No, I'm fine.</i>

130
00:09:13,428 --> 00:09:15,847
<i>How is your day going?
Abby off to school?</i>

131
00:09:16,556 --> 00:09:18,266
MIKE: Uh, not yet.
She's, uh...

132
00:09:18,349 --> 00:09:19,684
she's around here
somewhere.

133
00:09:20,185 --> 00:09:23,021
Jeremiah's on his <i>way</i> over to help
me keep painting the new house.

134
00:09:23,646 --> 00:09:24,647
VANESSA: <i>Great.</i>

135
00:09:24,731 --> 00:09:26,232
Um, I just wanted
to see if we were...

136
00:09:26,316 --> 00:09:28,359
we're still good for...
for dinner later.

137
00:09:28,443 --> 00:09:30,528
VANESSA: <i>Yeah. Yeah.</i>
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

138
00:09:30,612 --> 00:09:31,613
Definitely.

139
00:09:32,113 --> 00:09:33,573
It'll be good to get out.

140
00:09:34,699 --> 00:09:37,410
Um, hey, I gotta run, but
I'll, uh... I'll see you later, then.

141
00:09:37,494 --> 00:09:38,995
<i>Bye.</i>
Okay. Bye.

142
00:09:40,747 --> 00:09:42,499
(BEEPS)
(SIGHS)

143
00:09:44,959 --> 00:09:46,503
So, have you
kissed her yet?

144
00:09:47,295 --> 00:09:48,421
No.

145
00:09:48,505 --> 00:09:51,424
Abs, it's not... it's not like
that. We're... we're just friends.

146
00:09:51,508 --> 00:09:53,176
Then <i>why</i> are you going
on a date?

147
00:09:54,135 --> 00:09:56,930
It's not a date. Then
<i>why</i> can't I come along?

148
00:09:57,514 --> 00:09:58,723
Because you can't.

149
00:09:58,807 --> 00:09:59,808
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

150
00:09:59,891 --> 00:10:01,768
That's what
I thought. (CHUCKLES)

151
00:10:03,061 --> 00:10:05,605
Abby!
The Abbittyville Horror.

152
00:10:05,688 --> 00:10:06,773
The Abbster.

153
00:10:06,856 --> 00:10:08,733
Word up.
(BOTH MIMIC EXPLOSIONS)

154
00:10:08,817 --> 00:10:10,985
What's happening?
You're growing like a weed.

155
00:10:11,069 --> 00:10:12,403
ABBY: Uh,
I got to run.

156
00:10:12,487 --> 00:10:13,696
You sure you don't
wanna stay and paint?

157
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:14,781
I'll trade places
with you.

158
00:10:14,864 --> 00:10:15,865
(CHUCKLES)

159
00:10:15,949 --> 00:10:18,243
Thanks, but I think
they'd notice at school.

160
00:10:18,326 --> 00:10:20,078
Probably.
ABBY: Bye.

161
00:10:20,161 --> 00:10:22,121
See you later.
ABBY: Bryson!

162
00:10:22,205 --> 00:10:23,206
Bryson, wait.

163
00:10:23,289 --> 00:10:24,290
You dropped this.

164
00:10:25,375 --> 00:10:26,626
JEREMIAH: You know,
she's a good kid.

165
00:10:26,709 --> 00:10:27,836
She is.

166
00:10:28,545 --> 00:10:30,046
She's got a really good
heart. (BUS DOOR CLOSES)

167
00:10:30,129 --> 00:10:33,049
So, you still going on that
date with Vanessa later?

168
00:10:33,132 --> 00:10:34,133
(BUS ENGINE WHIRRING)

169
00:10:34,217 --> 00:10:35,218
It's not a date.

170
00:10:35,301 --> 00:10:38,596
Just a couple of adults having
dinner together, you know?

171
00:10:38,680 --> 00:10:40,139
Mmm.

172
00:10:42,308 --> 00:10:45,478
Listen, I wish you two all
the happiness in the world.

173
00:10:46,062 --> 00:10:47,230
All I'm saying is

174
00:10:48,398 --> 00:10:49,983
she's got crazy eyes, Mike.

175
00:10:51,317 --> 00:10:52,819
She's not crazy, okay?

176
00:10:53,945 --> 00:10:55,488
(PEOPLE TALKING INDISTINCTLY
AND LAUGHING)

177
00:10:55,572 --> 00:10:57,282
Ooh, speaking
of crazy.

178
00:10:57,365 --> 00:10:58,992
Ever since your aunt
went around

179
00:10:59,075 --> 00:11:01,160
telling stories about
killer teddy bears,

180
00:11:01,244 --> 00:11:03,162
the whole damn town's
lost its mind.

181
00:11:03,246 --> 00:11:05,081
You know, I'll be happy
when this weekend's over.

182
00:11:05,164 --> 00:11:06,291
All the festival
stuff's done,

183
00:11:06,374 --> 00:11:08,543
and people maybe just
will go back to normal.

184
00:11:08,626 --> 00:11:09,627
Yeah.

185
00:11:09,711 --> 00:11:12,255
People are obsessed
with that old pizzeria.

186
00:11:12,338 --> 00:11:14,299
Yeah, I heard they had your
aunt committed, by the way.

187
00:11:14,382 --> 00:11:15,800
That's terrible.

188
00:11:16,926 --> 00:11:18,136
Yeah, it's a real shame.

189
00:11:18,219 --> 00:11:20,555
Hey, you sure your aunt
just made those stories up,

190
00:11:20,638 --> 00:11:22,640
like, out of the blue?

191
00:11:22,724 --> 00:11:24,017
MIKE: Hey, you know what?
Why don't we just keep it

192
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:26,853
between you and me that
Abby's even related to her?

193
00:11:26,936 --> 00:11:27,979
You know,
she's been through a lot,

194
00:11:28,855 --> 00:11:30,356
and she doesn't like
that kind of attention.

195
00:11:30,440 --> 00:11:32,859
So then Chica tried to shove
me into a springlock suit.

196
00:11:32,942 --> 00:11:34,819
But then Mike came in,
and he had a Taser,

197
00:11:34,903 --> 00:11:36,613
and he shot her
in the face with it.

198
00:11:36,696 --> 00:11:38,072
I ran for
the dining room

199
00:11:38,156 --> 00:11:39,532
just as Foxy
came off the stage

200
00:11:39,616 --> 00:11:41,034
and started
chasing me down.

201
00:11:41,618 --> 00:11:43,202
Luckily,
Vanessa saved me.

202
00:11:43,286 --> 00:11:45,663
But then
the Yellow Rabbit came,

203
00:11:45,747 --> 00:11:47,123
and he attacked us.

204
00:11:47,206 --> 00:11:49,417
He got Vanessa.
He stabbed her.

205
00:11:50,251 --> 00:11:51,544
She's okay now.

206
00:11:51,628 --> 00:11:53,713
So, what happened
to the Yellow Rabbit?

207
00:11:53,796 --> 00:11:56,341
The springlocks went off
inside of his own suit

208
00:11:56,424 --> 00:11:57,717
and crushed him alive.

209
00:11:59,052 --> 00:12:00,803
They say his body's
still at Freddy's,

210
00:12:01,429 --> 00:12:04,891
hidden in a secret room
that nobody's ever seen.

211
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:07,185
You're crazy.

212
00:12:09,270 --> 00:12:10,730
Want to sit
with us at lunch?

213
00:12:12,231 --> 00:12:13,232
Sure.

214
00:12:15,234 --> 00:12:16,778
Are you ever gonna
go back?

215
00:12:16,861 --> 00:12:18,029
To Freddy's,
I mean.

216
00:12:19,614 --> 00:12:20,782
I would, but...

217
00:12:22,659 --> 00:12:23,660
my friends...

218
00:12:24,535 --> 00:12:26,037
The animatronics
are broken.

219
00:12:26,120 --> 00:12:28,706
Mike says that he'll
fix them someday, but...

220
00:12:30,124 --> 00:12:31,960
he's been saying that
for a while now.

221
00:12:34,671 --> 00:12:37,048
Wait, so do you actually
believe anything I'm saying?

222
00:12:37,131 --> 00:12:40,551
'Cause I'm pretty sure everyone
else just thinks I'm making this stuff up.

223
00:12:41,636 --> 00:12:43,304
I believe in UFOs.

224
00:12:43,888 --> 00:12:45,431
And ghosts.

225
00:12:45,515 --> 00:12:48,351
So <i>why</i> not
haunted animatronics?

226
00:12:49,102 --> 00:12:50,687
TEACHER: Young ladies,
young men, let's go.

227
00:12:50,770 --> 00:12:52,188
Yeah.
(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

228
00:12:52,271 --> 00:12:54,107
(MECHANICAL WHIRRING)

229
00:12:54,190 --> 00:12:55,274
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

230
00:12:56,526 --> 00:12:57,944
(WHIRRING)

231
00:12:58,027 --> 00:13:00,279
MR. BERG: Everyone,
eyes to me.

232
00:13:01,531 --> 00:13:03,992
I just want to,
uh, remind you

233
00:13:04,784 --> 00:13:06,494
that our robotics
presentation

234
00:13:06,577 --> 00:13:10,206
at the science fair
is this Saturday.

235
00:13:10,957 --> 00:13:14,002
Some of you
have been swept up

236
00:13:14,085 --> 00:13:17,922
in the stupidity
that is this Freddy Fest.

237
00:13:18,006 --> 00:13:20,800
Actually, Mr. Berg,
it's Fazfest.

238
00:13:20,883 --> 00:13:22,969
I don't care
what it's called.

239
00:13:23,052 --> 00:13:24,846
It's a mockery
of everything

240
00:13:24,929 --> 00:13:27,140
that true robotics
stands for.

241
00:13:27,223 --> 00:13:29,809
We're making real
robots here, people.

242
00:13:29,892 --> 00:13:31,936
I want each
and every one of you

243
00:13:32,020 --> 00:13:34,105
to be at that science fair
on Saturday,

244
00:13:34,188 --> 00:13:35,857
whether you're entering
or not.

245
00:13:36,858 --> 00:13:39,944
Or you can expect
a big, fat "F."

246
00:13:40,028 --> 00:13:42,321
"F" for "Fazfest"?

247
00:13:42,405 --> 00:13:43,990
(STUDENTS LAUGH)
MR. BERG: No.

248
00:13:44,073 --> 00:13:45,324
"F" for "fail."

249
00:13:47,076 --> 00:13:50,163
Don't waste your time.
Let's get to work.

250
00:13:50,246 --> 00:13:51,706
(MECHANICAL WHIRRING)

251
00:13:54,917 --> 00:13:56,544
(ELECTRICAL CRACKLING)
(CLATTERING)

252
00:13:58,588 --> 00:13:59,922
MR. BERG:
Ms. Schmidt.

253
00:14:00,423 --> 00:14:01,424
According to this,

254
00:14:02,425 --> 00:14:04,844
you're planning
on showing

255
00:14:04,927 --> 00:14:08,473
whatever this is,
Saturday, at the science fair.

256
00:14:08,556 --> 00:14:10,141
Certainly, I don't have
to remind you

257
00:14:10,224 --> 00:14:13,811
how important this event
is to the school.

258
00:14:13,895 --> 00:14:16,189
We're defending a
three-year winning streak.

259
00:14:17,565 --> 00:14:18,858
I'll be ready.

260
00:14:18,941 --> 00:14:20,610
Yeah, that...
that's just the thing.

261
00:14:21,611 --> 00:14:23,488
I don't think
you will be ready.

262
00:14:24,864 --> 00:14:29,035
Ms. Schmidt, robotics...
isn't for everyone.

263
00:14:29,952 --> 00:14:31,954
There's no shame
in taking a seat

264
00:14:32,038 --> 00:14:33,164
for the good
of the team.

265
00:14:34,040 --> 00:14:36,959
Now, look, look, look, what's
our... what's our school motto?

266
00:14:37,627 --> 00:14:39,670
"Otters otter help
each otter."

267
00:14:39,754 --> 00:14:40,880
Right.

268
00:14:42,256 --> 00:14:43,257
Right.

269
00:14:44,050 --> 00:14:45,843
Be a good little otter.

270
00:14:50,473 --> 00:14:52,558
(CHUCKLES SARCASTICALLY)

271
00:14:53,643 --> 00:14:56,229
He's rough on everyone.
Don't let him get to you.

272
00:15:02,360 --> 00:15:03,611
I'm surprised
you haven't tried

273
00:15:03,694 --> 00:15:04,904
to fix your friends
yourself.

274
00:15:04,987 --> 00:15:06,114
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC PLAYING)

275
00:15:06,197 --> 00:15:07,240
But I bet you could.

276
00:15:13,621 --> 00:15:15,581
MIKE: Abs, is that you?
Yeah.

277
00:15:16,499 --> 00:15:17,917
All right.
Perfect timing.

278
00:15:18,876 --> 00:15:20,002
You wanna do this for me?

279
00:15:21,045 --> 00:15:22,755
You're hopeless.
(CHUCKLES)

280
00:15:24,173 --> 00:15:25,174
How was your day?

281
00:15:26,425 --> 00:15:27,426
Fine.

282
00:15:27,927 --> 00:15:29,846
Um, anything exciting happen?

283
00:15:29,929 --> 00:15:31,180
Not really.

284
00:15:32,557 --> 00:15:33,558
Okay.

285
00:15:36,853 --> 00:15:37,854
There.

286
00:15:37,937 --> 00:15:39,522
What would you do
without me?

287
00:15:40,189 --> 00:15:41,607
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

288
00:15:41,691 --> 00:15:42,692
Thank you very much.

289
00:15:43,526 --> 00:15:45,153
Okay. Uh...

290
00:15:46,028 --> 00:15:49,532
Abs, I'm leaving a...
a 20 on the table

291
00:15:49,615 --> 00:15:51,367
so you can...
you can order a pizza.

292
00:15:51,450 --> 00:15:53,744
You remember how
to call and everything?

293
00:15:53,828 --> 00:15:55,621
Of course. I'm 11.

294
00:15:55,705 --> 00:15:56,873
I'm not a baby.

295
00:15:57,373 --> 00:15:58,749
I know. I know.

296
00:15:58,833 --> 00:16:01,085
Anything else you need
from me before I go?

297
00:16:01,169 --> 00:16:02,962
You gonna watch
some TV or what?

298
00:16:05,506 --> 00:16:08,593
Maybe I could go
see my friends?

299
00:16:11,929 --> 00:16:14,432
You mean, like,
your friends from school?

300
00:16:15,224 --> 00:16:17,435
I meant Chica
and the others.

301
00:16:18,060 --> 00:16:19,103
Those friends.

302
00:16:20,062 --> 00:16:22,732
Look, Abs,
we talked about this.

303
00:16:24,025 --> 00:16:25,735
Okay, you can't
go back there.

304
00:16:25,818 --> 00:16:27,069
They're broken.

305
00:16:29,822 --> 00:16:31,490
Now, one day,
I'm gonna go fix them,

306
00:16:31,574 --> 00:16:33,868
but until then,
maybe you could try

307
00:16:33,951 --> 00:16:35,620
making some friends
with some real kids.

308
00:16:37,079 --> 00:16:38,873
My friends
are real kids.

309
00:16:39,790 --> 00:16:40,833
(TV BUZZES ON)

310
00:16:40,917 --> 00:16:43,628
LISA: (OVER TV) <i>We are
in the haunted courthouse.</i>

311
00:16:43,711 --> 00:16:46,380
(EERIE SHRIEKING AND WHOOSHING
SOUND EFFECTS PLAY OVER TV)

312
00:16:47,381 --> 00:16:49,550
(CREAKING OVER TV)
<i>Did you guys hear that?</i>

313
00:16:50,218 --> 00:16:51,761
ROB: (OVER TV) <i>Hear what?</i>

314
00:16:52,637 --> 00:16:53,638
Look, you're right.

315
00:16:54,805 --> 00:16:56,807
Abs, I'm sorry, okay?

316
00:16:56,891 --> 00:16:58,601
It's just that it's...
it's complicated,

317
00:16:58,684 --> 00:16:59,852
but we can talk
about it later.

318
00:16:59,936 --> 00:17:01,646
I have to go.
Yeah.

319
00:17:02,605 --> 00:17:04,941
(EERIE WHOOSHING OVER TV)

320
00:17:05,024 --> 00:17:06,525
LISA: <i>I don't know...</i>
(CONTINUES INDISTINCTLY)

321
00:17:06,609 --> 00:17:07,610
I love you.

322
00:17:09,153 --> 00:17:10,154
ABBY: Mmm-hmm.

323
00:17:13,282 --> 00:17:14,951
All right, don't... don't
watch too much of that show.

324
00:17:15,034 --> 00:17:16,285
It'll give you
nightmares, okay?

325
00:17:16,953 --> 00:17:17,954
ROB: (OVER TV)
<i>You getting this?</i>

326
00:17:18,955 --> 00:17:20,081
(KEYS JINGLING)

327
00:17:21,499 --> 00:17:23,251
I'll be back later.
(DOORKNOB RATTLES)

328
00:17:23,334 --> 00:17:25,336
(INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING)

329
00:17:26,545 --> 00:17:27,588
(DOOR SHUTS)

330
00:17:29,548 --> 00:17:31,550
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION
CONTINUES OVER TV)

331
00:17:38,808 --> 00:17:40,810
(GENTLE PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

332
00:17:47,483 --> 00:17:49,568
WAITER: Pardon me, sir.
Mmm. Oh.

333
00:17:49,652 --> 00:17:50,861
There we are.

334
00:17:52,446 --> 00:17:53,447
Thank you.

335
00:17:57,326 --> 00:17:58,327
Hi.

336
00:18:04,250 --> 00:18:05,543
So this is
what it's like?

337
00:18:06,585 --> 00:18:07,586
MIKE: What?

338
00:18:08,087 --> 00:18:09,171
Being normal.

339
00:18:10,298 --> 00:18:11,465
"Normal."

340
00:18:11,549 --> 00:18:13,384
Is that... Are we...
We're normal now?

341
00:18:13,968 --> 00:18:15,469
I think we're doing
pretty good,

342
00:18:15,970 --> 00:18:17,805
considering what
we've been through.

343
00:18:20,474 --> 00:18:22,143
I just have too much
time on my hands.

344
00:18:22,226 --> 00:18:24,603
It'll be better when I
can get back to work.

345
00:18:24,687 --> 00:18:25,980
No, I think
you're doing great.

346
00:18:26,689 --> 00:18:28,524
I mean, didn't you...
You signed up for, like...

347
00:18:28,607 --> 00:18:30,651
like, biking classes,
right? Or... Spin class.

348
00:18:30,735 --> 00:18:33,029
Spin class. Yeah, yeah. I've
been going a couple of weeks.

349
00:18:33,112 --> 00:18:34,864
Okay. I even made some friends.

350
00:18:34,947 --> 00:18:35,948
Friends.

351
00:18:36,782 --> 00:18:38,534
What's that like?
(CHUCKLES)

352
00:18:43,205 --> 00:18:44,957
WAITER: Pardon
my reach, madam. Oh.

353
00:18:48,210 --> 00:18:49,962
They... they love
doing that here.

354
00:18:50,046 --> 00:18:51,047
(CHUCKLES)

355
00:18:53,090 --> 00:18:55,468
Um, you... you look
great, by the way.

356
00:18:59,638 --> 00:19:00,639
So do you.

357
00:19:02,808 --> 00:19:04,810
(SOFTLY) This is a date. What?

358
00:19:06,270 --> 00:19:07,897
What?
Did you say something?

359
00:19:07,980 --> 00:19:10,066
No, I... I said... I said this
is a... a lovely day, a day.

360
00:19:10,149 --> 00:19:11,734
Day. Today's been
a great day. Yeah.

361
00:19:11,817 --> 00:19:12,818
(CLEARS THROAT)

362
00:19:14,904 --> 00:19:16,322
Let me guess,
Abby tie that for you?

363
00:19:17,740 --> 00:19:19,075
She did. Yeah.
How is she?

364
00:19:19,158 --> 00:19:20,159
She's good.

365
00:19:20,242 --> 00:19:22,578
Well, some days are good.
Some days, she, uh...

366
00:19:24,914 --> 00:19:25,998
she really misses them...

367
00:19:27,333 --> 00:19:28,459
her "friends."

368
00:19:28,542 --> 00:19:32,129
And, uh, I don't know
how to talk to her about it.

369
00:19:33,756 --> 00:19:35,549
I know you're trying
to protect her, Mike,

370
00:19:35,633 --> 00:19:37,718
but this story
that they're broken,

371
00:19:38,260 --> 00:19:40,096
that you're gonna fix
those animatronics,

372
00:19:40,679 --> 00:19:42,348
it's only giving her
false hope.

373
00:19:42,932 --> 00:19:44,016
Just be honest.

374
00:19:45,142 --> 00:19:46,185
Honest?

375
00:19:47,520 --> 00:19:48,687
What?

376
00:19:48,771 --> 00:19:49,772
MIKE: Uh, nothing.

377
00:19:54,026 --> 00:19:57,446
So, you wanna... tell me
about your bad dream?

378
00:19:57,530 --> 00:19:59,949
It's always
the same. (CHUCKLES)

379
00:20:00,032 --> 00:20:01,951
We don't need
to talk about that.

380
00:20:02,535 --> 00:20:03,869
Your dad?

381
00:20:03,953 --> 00:20:06,372
Look, Vanessa, I was
thinking, do you remember how

382
00:20:06,455 --> 00:20:08,833
I would use my dreams to confront
what happened with Garrett?

383
00:20:09,542 --> 00:20:12,336
I mean, I admit I probably
slept a bit too much,

384
00:20:12,420 --> 00:20:14,380
but it really
helped me a lot.

385
00:20:14,880 --> 00:20:16,340
I think it can
help you, too.

386
00:20:18,008 --> 00:20:19,009
I...

387
00:20:19,635 --> 00:20:22,179
I... I don't think
that's a good idea.

388
00:20:24,432 --> 00:20:26,100
You're never gonna
be free of your dad

389
00:20:26,934 --> 00:20:29,019
until you deal with some of
the mess he left in your head.

390
00:20:30,271 --> 00:20:33,524
I just... I want us to be
able to move past all of this.

391
00:20:34,275 --> 00:20:35,276
You can do it.

392
00:20:36,152 --> 00:20:37,153
At least try.

393
00:20:37,945 --> 00:20:38,946
Just once.

394
00:20:41,157 --> 00:20:42,491
(KEYS JANGLE)
(DOORKNOB RATTLES)

395
00:20:43,576 --> 00:20:44,702
Abs, I'm back.

396
00:20:50,416 --> 00:20:51,417
Abby?

397
00:20:52,334 --> 00:20:53,377
Abs, did you eat?

398
00:20:53,461 --> 00:20:54,962
(FOREBODING MUSIC PLAYING)

399
00:20:55,045 --> 00:20:57,673
Abby? Abby?

400
00:21:00,092 --> 00:21:01,093
Abby?

401
00:21:01,177 --> 00:21:02,303
(RUNNING FOOTSTEPS)

402
00:21:15,191 --> 00:21:16,692
{\an8}(DOOR RATTLES AND CREAKS)

403
00:21:16,775 --> 00:21:19,236
{\an8}(INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING)

404
00:21:43,552 --> 00:21:44,845
(LIGHTS CLANK ON)

405
00:21:51,101 --> 00:21:52,978
(SOBBING SOFTLY)

406
00:22:00,861 --> 00:22:01,862
Hey.

407
00:22:04,740 --> 00:22:05,950
Abs, I'm sorry. I...

408
00:22:06,742 --> 00:22:07,993
I didn't know
how to tell you.

409
00:22:10,412 --> 00:22:11,956
Where are they?

410
00:22:13,290 --> 00:22:16,627
I mean, there's...
pieces of them here,

411
00:22:16,710 --> 00:22:17,711
pieces of them there.

412
00:22:17,795 --> 00:22:19,004
No, that's not
what I mean.

413
00:22:20,339 --> 00:22:22,007
Where are my friends?

414
00:22:27,221 --> 00:22:28,681
Look, Abs, I, um...

415
00:22:31,267 --> 00:22:32,268
I don't know.

416
00:22:33,561 --> 00:22:35,271
You know, maybe, um...

417
00:22:37,189 --> 00:22:38,399
maybe they're in heaven.

418
00:22:39,775 --> 00:22:40,985
Wouldn't you
want that for them?

419
00:22:42,695 --> 00:22:43,696
{\an8}Yeah.

420
00:22:45,030 --> 00:22:46,282
{\an8}I would like that.

421
00:22:47,533 --> 00:22:49,743
I'm sorry I didn't
tell you sooner, okay?

422
00:22:51,495 --> 00:22:52,496
But you know what?

423
00:22:53,664 --> 00:22:56,875
They're always gonna be
right here.

424
00:23:00,838 --> 00:23:02,548
That's really cheesy.

425
00:23:02,631 --> 00:23:03,632
(LAUGHS)

426
00:23:04,883 --> 00:23:07,052
Yeah, it's a little cheesy.
It's extremely cheesy.

427
00:23:07,136 --> 00:23:08,262
All right,
all right, all right.

428
00:23:11,307 --> 00:23:12,308
You know what?

429
00:23:12,391 --> 00:23:13,934
Come with me.
I got an idea.

430
00:23:16,312 --> 00:23:17,313
<i>Okay, young lady,</i>

431
00:23:17,396 --> 00:23:20,482
you have
one million tickets.

432
00:23:21,108 --> 00:23:23,027
What can I get you? Do
you want some, uh... Oh.

433
00:23:23,611 --> 00:23:26,238
What about orange
gummy candies?

434
00:23:27,489 --> 00:23:28,741
No?

435
00:23:28,824 --> 00:23:29,825
Okay.

436
00:23:30,492 --> 00:23:32,161
Uh, we got...

437
00:23:36,624 --> 00:23:38,584
Uh, let's see. Oh.

438
00:23:38,667 --> 00:23:39,668
What about this?

439
00:23:42,796 --> 00:23:44,298
(TOY VOICE HUMMING
<i>TOREADOR SONG</i>) Oh.

440
00:23:44,381 --> 00:23:46,258
Well, maybe not.

441
00:23:46,759 --> 00:23:47,760
(HUMMING STOPS)

442
00:23:58,520 --> 00:23:59,980
What you got there?

443
00:24:00,064 --> 00:24:02,232
It's a... Faztalker.

444
00:24:02,316 --> 00:24:04,735
MIKE: "Realistic
voice interaction device.

445
00:24:04,818 --> 00:24:06,278
"Talk to us anytime."

446
00:24:06,362 --> 00:24:07,363
Is that what you want?

447
00:24:10,199 --> 00:24:11,450
Yeah.
Yeah?

448
00:24:11,533 --> 00:24:13,243
Sold.
One million tickets.

449
00:24:13,327 --> 00:24:14,328
(CHUCKLES)

450
00:24:14,953 --> 00:24:16,205
Now let's go home.

451
00:24:18,457 --> 00:24:20,000
I thought you liked
orange gummy candy.

452
00:24:20,751 --> 00:24:24,296
Well, I did, until I ate that
whole bag at Christmas.

453
00:24:24,380 --> 00:24:25,464
Oh.

454
00:24:25,547 --> 00:24:27,299
And you threw it up
everywhere. Yeah.

455
00:24:27,383 --> 00:24:30,302
That was like an
orange slime waterfall.

456
00:24:30,386 --> 00:24:31,887
It was really rough.
Don't remind me.

457
00:24:42,690 --> 00:24:44,692
(OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING)

458
00:25:03,585 --> 00:25:04,670
(CRICKETS CHIRPING)

459
00:25:04,753 --> 00:25:06,463
(ENGINE REVVING)

460
00:25:07,923 --> 00:25:10,426
<i>(ABSOLUTELY (STORY OF A
GIRL)</i> PLAYING OVER STEREO)

461
00:25:10,509 --> 00:25:12,261
You sure I'm going
the right way?

462
00:25:12,845 --> 00:25:13,846
Uh, yeah.

463
00:25:13,929 --> 00:25:15,013
No, it should
be up ahead.

464
00:25:16,473 --> 00:25:18,642
(SIGHS)How'd you guys
find out about this place again?

465
00:25:20,602 --> 00:25:21,854
Security guard
who works there.

466
00:25:21,937 --> 00:25:23,731
His name is... Mike?

467
00:25:23,814 --> 00:25:26,525
I don't care who he is, as
long as we have permission.

468
00:25:26,608 --> 00:25:29,445
Trust me, we have
VIP treatment this time.

469
00:25:29,528 --> 00:25:31,113
No breaking and
entering required.

470
00:25:34,032 --> 00:25:36,368
Yeah, there.
There it is.

471
00:25:36,452 --> 00:25:38,454
(EERIE MUSIC PLAYING)

472
00:26:00,267 --> 00:26:01,477
ROB: Freddy Fazbear's Pizza.

473
00:26:02,060 --> 00:26:03,687
(CHUCKLES) I used to
come here when I was a kid.

474
00:26:04,354 --> 00:26:06,148
Not this one
you didn't.

475
00:26:06,231 --> 00:26:08,233
You're thinking of
the franchise location.

476
00:26:10,444 --> 00:26:12,571
<i>This is the original.</i>

477
00:26:13,614 --> 00:26:15,407
Nobody's been here
for decades.

478
00:26:16,158 --> 00:26:17,951
<i>This location came
before the other one.</i>

479
00:26:18,452 --> 00:26:19,953
So, what happened here?

480
00:26:21,371 --> 00:26:23,957
Some little girl
got murdered.

481
00:26:24,041 --> 00:26:25,459
Whole thing got swept
under the rug.

482
00:26:25,542 --> 00:26:26,919
ALEX: (IN SPOOKY VOICE)
And now,

483
00:26:27,002 --> 00:26:29,797
her soul wanders
these forgotten halls,

484
00:26:29,880 --> 00:26:32,216
tortured and alone.
(LAUGHING)

485
00:26:34,009 --> 00:26:35,844
(SCREAMS AND PANTS)

486
00:26:35,928 --> 00:26:36,929
Dude.

487
00:26:37,763 --> 00:26:40,766
Uh, sorry.
You startled us.

488
00:26:42,434 --> 00:26:43,435
You must be Mike.

489
00:26:44,853 --> 00:26:46,563
It's Michael, actually.

490
00:26:51,026 --> 00:26:52,277
Call me Michael.

491
00:26:56,865 --> 00:26:57,866
So?

492
00:26:58,367 --> 00:26:59,368
Are you ready
for the tour?

493
00:27:00,202 --> 00:27:02,079
(OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING)
(DOOR RATTLES AND CREAKS)

494
00:27:02,162 --> 00:27:03,539
(LIGHTS BUZZING)

495
00:27:09,211 --> 00:27:10,295
(DOOR SHUTS)

496
00:27:14,091 --> 00:27:15,175
Welcome to Freddy's.

497
00:27:18,178 --> 00:27:19,930
You're cool
if we record everything?

498
00:27:20,013 --> 00:27:21,223
MICHAEL: Of course.

499
00:27:22,599 --> 00:27:23,725
<i>That's why you're here,
isn't it?</i>

500
00:27:25,394 --> 00:27:27,020
(LAUGHING)No way.

